title: Hear Ye! Smile And Then Go Away, Please!
text:
For the price and the chuckle it gives me, this little sign is worth every penny. It states a simple and humorous message, with lightly painted lettering on a flat plywood plank, and it includes a fabric hanger. The hanger holes are nicely pre-drilled if you decide to use another material to display it. I like the current look, but I may also try using a piece of flexible 'older' wire for a different style.

The sign's appearance is rustic and therefore looks charmingly aged. It is also very porous. I will add a coat or two of matte polyurethane (or similar) to seal it well since our climate is brutal. I won't need to buy anything extra because I think every household (including mine) has leftover varnish of some kind; it'll take less than 5 minutes, and it's entirely optional. The seller or buyer may intend for the sign to continue developing an aged appearance, and if so, it's one less process for the seller to complete (sealing the sign), so likely priced less for the buyer.

I am an extremely friendly person, so hanging a "no solicitors" sign makes me feel a little unsocial, but it's a necessity unless I want to answer the door to salespeople nearly every day. This homemade sign is perfect for people like me. I send a clear message in a firm, yet funny way. What's great, too, is that I travel throughout my city for a living and I've only seen one other sign like this one, so it still feels like a unique and fresh idea!

The sellers at Trimble Crafts are professional, respond quickly, and are very customer oriented. This is always appreciated! Their product ships from their state, not a warehouse, and they mail your item quickly! I am very pleased with my purchase! Hope this helps!​

Love the peace lamps, well made with quality materials and obviously a lot of care. I spent a lot of time (and too much money) trying to do something like this myself, and was finally SO HAPPY to have found these peace lamps -- which are EXACTLY what I wanted!

Olive oil lamps can be tricky to use at first if you are used to the idea of using very flammable liquids to burn wicks. The oil does NOT like to travel up very far on a wick (maybe 2 inches)? So I got some squat (short) mason jars to use. I have not used them yet, but have studied up on this a lot. Olive oil burns slowly and if you want a LOT of light you may need to buy these in multiple if you are going to use this as your main light source , etc. but really the fact that they are nontoxic to burn indoors and generate no soot -- how cool is that?! Not only that, but if you somehow manage to spill a lamp over while it is lit, it is (of all oil lamps) the very most UNLIKELY to cause a fire! (This is because the olive oil is very finicky on where the wick is placed and it needs the wick to burn.)
